title: Aust bonds firmer after Fed minutes
text:
Thu, Aug 20, 2015, 11:55 AM AEST - Australia Markets close in 4 hrs 5 mins Aust bonds firmer after Fed minutes AAP â€“ 2 hours 43 minutes ago Recommend 
The Australian bond market is firmer after the release of the US Federal Reserve minutes and weaker than expected American inflation data. 
St George senior economist Janu Chan said Australian bond futures prices strengthened in line with US Treasuries. 
"US treasury yields fell (prices rose) after the minutes lessened the chance of an official rate hike in September and raised some concerns about low inflation," she said. 
"Market pricing now imply just an eight per cent chance of a 25 basis points hike in September and a 56 per cent chance in December." 
At 0830 AEST on Thursday, the September 2015 10-year bond futures contract was trading at 97.275 (implying a yield of 2.725 per cent), up from 97.225 (2.775 per cent) on Wednesday. 
The September 2015 three-year bond futures contract was at 98.110 (1.890 per cent), up from 98.060 (1.940 per cent). 
KEY MOVEMENTS: 
* CGS 5.5pct Jan 2018, 1.904pct, from 1.901pct on Wednesday 
* CGS 4.25pct April 2026, 2.824pct, from 2.825pct 
Sydney Futures Exchange prices: 
* September 2015 bill futures, 97.890, unchanged 
* December 2015 bill futures, 97.960, from 97.950 
(*Closes taken at 1630 AEST previous local session) 
Source: IRESS
